Chapter 3 Linear Regression

This notebook is a rough outline of Chapter 3 of An Introduction to Statistical Learning (James et al.(2013)1).

The authors do not provide code for the analysis or figures used throughout each chapter. They do however provide access to some of the data. This notebook uses the data to recreate some of the analysis and figures from the chapter.

Setup

library(ISLR)
library(tidyverse)
library(patchwork)
theme_set(theme_bw())

# Given a filename, return the filepath. Default folder is the `data` folder in the current working directory.
get_path <- function(filename) {
  str_c(getwd(), "data", filename, sep = "/")
}

# Return a table (matrix) of the coefficients of a linear model:
get_regression_coefs <- function(model, rounding) {
  table <- summary(model)$coef
  return(round(table, rounding))
}

FIGURE 3.1

# Linear model:
mod <- lm(sales ~ TV, data = Ad)

# Get a data frame of the model input data, fitted values and residuals
mod_data <- data.frame(mod$model, # the moderndive::get_regression_points() function is nice, but better to use base R in case something changes
           sales_hat = mod$fitted.values)

# Plot:
colors_3.1 <- c("darkred" = "#cd2136",
             "darkblue" = "#37409e",
             "grey" = "#ACABAB")

ggplot(Ad) +
  geom_abline(aes(intercept = mod$coefficients[1], slope = mod$coefficients[2]),
              color = colors_3.1["darkblue"]) + # geom_abline extends in either direction, geom_smooth does not
  geom_segment(data = mod_data,
               aes(x = TV, xend = TV,
                   y = sales_hat, yend = sales),
               color = colors_3.1["grey"]) +
  geom_point(aes(TV, sales),
             color = colors_3.1["darkred"]) +
  labs(x = "TV", y = "Sales",
       title = "FIGURE 3.1") +
  scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 300, by = 50)) +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(5, 25, by = 5)) +
  theme(panel.grid = element_blank())

FIGURE 3.3

colors_3.3 <- c("red" = "#EB1F2B",
             "darkblue" = "#37409E",
             "lightblue" = "#AACFED")

n <- 100
x1 <- rnorm(100, sd = 1)
y1 <- 2 + 3*x1 + rnorm(100, sd = 3)
coefs1 <- lsfit(x1, y1)$coef

p1 <- data.frame(x = x1, y = y1) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x, y)) +
  geom_point(size = 2, shape = 21) +
  geom_abline(intercept = coefs1[1], slope = coefs1[2],
              color = colors_3.3["darkblue"],
              size = 1) +
  geom_abline(intercept = 2, slope = 3,
              color = colors_3.3["red"],
              size = 1) +
  labs(x = "X", y = "Y") +
  lims(x = c(min(x1), max(x1)), y = c(min(y1), max(y1))) +
  theme(panel.grid = element_blank())

# Generate 10 different least squares lines on random data sets:
coefs <- matrix(0, ncol = 2, nrow = 10)
for(i in 1:10) {
  x <- rnorm(100, sd = 1)
  y <- 2 + 3*x + rnorm(100, sd = 3)
  lsfit_coefs <- lsfit(x, y)$coef
  coefs[i, 1] <- lsfit_coefs[1]
  coefs[i, 2] <- lsfit_coefs[2]
}

p2 <- data.frame(x = x1, y = y1) %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_abline(data = data.frame(coefs),
              aes(intercept = X1, slope = X2),
              color = colors_3.3["lightblue"]) +
  geom_abline(intercept = coefs1[1], slope = coefs1[2],
              color = colors_3.3["darkblue"],
              size = 1) +
  geom_abline(intercept = 2, slope = 3,
              color = colors_3.3["red"],
              size = 1) +
  labs(x = "X", y = "Y") +
  lims(x = c(min(x1), max(x1)), y = c(min(y1), max(y1))) +
  theme(panel.grid = element_blank())

p1 + p2 +plot_annotation(title = "FIGURE 3.3")

Manually calculate the 95% CI (matches text, page 67):

mod_summary <- summary(mod)
coefs <- mod_summary$coefficients
alpha <- 0.05
df <- nrow(Ad) - 2
t <- qt(1 - alpha/2, df)
str_interp("The ${100*(1 - alpha)}% CI for the intercept is [${round(coefs[1, 1] - t*coefs[1, 2], 3)}, ${round(coefs[1, 1] + t*coefs[1, 2], 3)}]")
[1] "The 95% CI for the intercept is [6.13, 7.935]"
str_interp("The ${100*(1 - alpha)}% CI for the slope is [${round(coefs[2, 1] - t*coefs[2, 2], 3)}, ${round(coefs[2, 1] + t*coefs[2, 2], 3)}]")
[1] "The 95% CI for the slope is [0.042, 0.053]"

Test \(H_0: \beta_1 = 0\):

t <- (coefs[2, 1])/coefs[2, 2] # matches the result in summary(mod) above
2 * (1 - pt(abs(t), df)) # p-value
[1] 0

FIGURE 3.7

lm1 <- lm(Balance ~ Income + Student, data = Credit)
lm2 <- lm(Balance ~ Income*Student, data = Credit)

grid <- expand_grid(Income = 0:150, Student = c("No", "Yes"))
grid$pred1 <- predict(lm1, newdata = grid)
grid$pred2 <- predict(lm2, newdata = grid)

colors <- c("#5DAADF", "#D45319") # blue, brown
p1 <- ggplot(grid) +
  geom_line(aes(Income, pred1, color = Student)) +
  labs(x = "Income", y = "Balance", color = NULL,
       title = "No interaction term") +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(200, 1400, 400), limits = c(0, 1500)) +
  scale_color_manual(breaks = c("Yes", "No"), labels = c("Student", "Non-student"), values = colors)

p2 <- ggplot(grid) +
  geom_line(aes(Income, pred2, color = Student)) +
  labs(x = "Income", y = "Balance", color = NULL,
       title = "With interaction term") +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(200, 1400, 400), limits = c(0, 1500)) +
  scale_color_manual(breaks = c("Yes", "No"), labels = c("Student", "Non-student"), values = colors)

p1 + p2 + plot_annotation("FIGURE 3.7") + plot_layout(guides = "collect")

Credit_subset <- Credit %>%

         limit = Limit)

R_sq2 <- lm(rating ~ ., data = Credit_subset) %>% summary() %>% .$r.squared
